LEVEL 1 — File Input + Save Compressed File

Features
-> Read from file (input.txt)
-> Generate Huffman codes
-> Save compressed output (compressed.txt)


1. Read from file (input.txt)
The program reads the original text data from a file instead of hardcoding it.
What happens:
-> Open input.txt
-> Read its contents into a string

Why is it important:
-> Makes your program work with real files (not just sample strings)
-> More practical and scalable


2. Generate Huffman Codes
This is the core step using Huffman Coding
What happens:
-> Count frequency of each character
-> Build a Huffman Tree using a min-heap
-> Assign binary codes:
-> Frequent characters → shorter codes
-> Rare characters → longer codes

Why is it important:
-> Reduces total number of bits needed
-> Achieves compression


3. Save compressed output (compressed.txt)
Convert original text into encoded binary string and store it.
What happens:
-> Replace each character with its Huffman code
-> Combine into a binary string
-> Write it to compressed.txt

Why is it important:
-> This is your compressed data
-> Can be stored/transmitted efficiently
